&quot;Huq, who has withdrawn her support from the cycling event next month&quot;

Shameful. It is these &quot;Tory activists&quot; who should be ashamed.

So the biggest mass participation cycle ride in the UK gets a
children's TV presenter to help promote it, and come along on the day.
Exactly what is needed for an event like that to get media coverage.
And these Tory twits turn it into a party political feud.

For God's sake, we cannot have a country where the Tories are &quot;pro
car&quot; and Labour is &quot;anti car&quot;.
(Hmmmm... may just be a slimy attempt to ingratiate themselves with
Mrs and Mrs Middle Emgland Car Owner).

And now the poor lass won't be coming along on the day. Shame on you.

ps. Now - if she were to reconsider, and come along on a bike wearing
that dress, there would eb a lot more than 32000 people turning up...

The plot thickens:

A spokesman for the Mayor of London denied he had indulged in a
&quot;political rant&quot; and said the event was held purely to promote the
merits of cycling.

&quot;There was no party political element to Konnie Huq's involvement in
the launch, it was merely to promote the Freewheel, a fun, free event
to encourage everyday cycling in London,&quot; the spokesman said.

He added: &quot;During the press conference, the Mayor and Jenny Jones
briefly referred to Barnet's spending on cycling and the Assembly
Member for Barnet's £10,000 taxi bill - far from being the 'political
rant' Mr Coleman suggests, this was a moment of jokey banter. It was
certainly not in any way party political - no political parties were
even mentioned.&quot;

http://entertainment.aol.co.uk/huq-angers-tories-over-mayor-event/art...
