On 2007-08-15, Pete &lt;peterstuden ... @gmail.com&gt; wrote:

<QUOTE PREVIOUSPOST="
&gt; So you reckon the speed bumps are to blame for road deaths? That's
&gt; ridiculous.
">

Speed humps generally are an utterly retarded idea. All the speed humps
I've seen only really affect people in small cars (who are likely to be
slow, timid drivers in the first place). A case in point is that they
put some in a local village at the start of summer. Any mid-size car
could travel over the bumps without slowing down since most of the bump
would pass between the wheels. Only small cars had to slow down. SUVs
could totally ignore them.

They caused the most vulnerable road users (cyclists and motorcyclists)
to have to leave their normal lane position and either go through on the
white stripe or in the gutter.

I've seen a speed bump cause an accident, too. They fitted full width
diagonal speed bumps on the perimiter road of the university I was at.
Again, large vehicles like SUVs could completely ignore them, but they
were responsible for me needing new ball joints on my ancient student
budget Mini every year (I never needed to replace them until they put
the speed bumps in). Cyclists had to get right in the gutter to avoid
the speed bumps. I saw a cyclist crash when he hit some debris in the
gutter while trying to avoid the bump, and the cyclist narrowly avoided
piling head on into a parked car (instead taking the &quot;softer&quot; option of
landing in a heap in the gravel, complete with plenty of road rash).

That's before getting onto the noise and pollution issues of forcing
cars to slow down and accelerate needlessly. They take drivers and
cyclists and motorcyclists attention off other traffic, instead to deal
with the speed hump. Pinch points and other &quot;traffic aggravating&quot;
measures are also dangerous to the most vulnerable road users (such as
cyclists). As is making sight lines worse - it's just inviting cyclists
to get rear ended. Having been rear ended by a car driver who didn't see
me recently, I can first hand tell you that this hurts.

Speed bumps are a moronic idea. I was glad to see the local village saw
sense and removed the speed humps they fitted only a month after putting
them in.

